The paper addresses learning problems for high dimensional data, which is a common topic in machine learning. The paper proposes an algorithmic framework for employing non-oblivious randomized reduction method for general empirical risk minimizing in machine learning tasks, which suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also mentions numerical problems such as matrix product approximation and low-rank matrix approximation, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also mentions matrix approximation error, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The paper also discusses classification, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper conducts experiments on both synthetic and real-world benchmark datasets, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category.
